## ApiSources-A1 API Source & Multi-Provider Architecture
**Status:** proposed
**Tags:** stack:both
**Depends on:** ApiSources-G1

## ApiSources-A1 API Source & Multi-Provider Architecture
**Status:** proposed
**Tags:** stack:both
**Depends on:** ApiSources-G1

A single hardcoded provider (Claude only) limits agent flexibility and cost optimization. Agents in different roles have different cognitive requirements — a routing Assistant needs a cheap/fast model, while an Architect needs a strong reasoning model. Multi-provider support enables per-agent model selection from any configured API source.

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph "Config Layer"
        CF[config.rs] -->|load| AS[ApiSource Store]
        CF -->|load| AC[AgentConfig Store]
    end
    subgraph "Provider Dispatch"
        DP[dispatch_chat] --> AP[Anthropic Provider]
        DP --> OP[OpenAI Provider]
        DP --> LP[Local/Ollama Provider]
    end
    subgraph "Pipeline"
        PE[PipelineEngine] -->|resolve| RC[RelayRegistry]
        RC -->|spawn from| AC
        AC -->|uses| AS
        AS -->|routes via| DP
    end

    PE -->|step| AG[AgentInstance]
    AG -->|chat via| DP
```

### Trigger Condition
When an agent is spawned, `resolve_model()` looks up the AgentConfig's `model_id` in the referenced ApiSource, then `dispatch_chat()` routes to the correct provider.

### Data Flow
`[AgentConfig.model_id] → [resolve_model() → find in ApiSource.models] → [dispatch_chat(provider, model)] → [SSE stream]`

### Design Highlight
Multi-provider dispatch enables per-agent model selection. OpenAI and Local share the same `/v1/chat/completions` format; only Anthropic differs. This minimizes SSE parsing paths from 3 to 2.

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| Multi-provider dispatcher with ApiSource configs | Per-agent model selection, cost optimization | More complex AI dispatch layer |
| Single provider with model tiers only | Simpler implementation | Locked into one provider |
| Runtime model registry (no config UI) | No UI needed | Users cannot manage API keys |

- Positive: Each agent can use the optimal provider + model for its task.
- Positive: First-startup auto-detection finds existing keys — zero config for most users.
- Negative: Three different SSE parsing paths must be maintained.
- Mitigation: OpenAI and Local share the same format; only Anthropic differs.

## ApiSources-A2 APIs Documentation View Architecture
**Status:** approved
**Tags:** stack:frontend

- Static documentation living in `specs/apis.ad`; rendered as a read-only view in the frontend
- Grouped by backend module: Forge, Relay, Config, Wiki, Raw
- Each entry shows HTTP method, route path, handler function, and one-line description
- Editable through the Specs workspace when `apis.ad` is updated

## ApiSources-A3 Model-First Agent Configuration Architecture
**Status:** approved
**Tags:** stack:both, module:api-sources
**Depends on:** ApiSources-G3

## Overview

Replace tier-based model selection (`model_tier: ModelTier`) with direct model references (`model_id: String`) in AgentConfig. This eliminates the brittle tier downgrade walk and ensures every agent resolves to a concrete, existing model.

## Problem

The current `resolve_model()` walks tiers downward when a preferred tier isn't available in the ApiSource. This produces silent downgrades — a "Pro" agent might silently run on a "Lite" model because the ApiSource lacks a Pro-tier model. The user has no visibility into this, and the agent quality suffers unpredictably.

## Solution

Store a concrete `model_id` (e.g., `"claude-sonnet-4-20250514"`) on each AgentConfig. Resolution becomes a direct lookup — no fallback walk. If the model_id doesn't exist in the ApiSource, fallback to first model with a log warning. Tier becomes a display-only tag on ModelDefinition.

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph "Config Layer"
        AC[AgentConfig.model_id: String]
        AC -->|references| MD[ModelDefinition.id]
        MD -->|display tag| MT[ModelTier: Min/Lite/Mid/Pro/Max]
    end
    subgraph "Resolution"
        RM[resolve_model] -->|find by model_id| AS[ApiSource.models]
        AS -->|not found| FB[Fallback: first model + log::warn]
        AS -->|found| MC[ModelConfig]
    end
    subgraph "Migration"
        OLD[Legacy: model_tier only] -->|assign_model_ids| NEW[model_id filled]
    end

    AC --> RM
```

### Trigger Condition

Resolution triggers every time an agent is spawned (relay pipeline step or chat turn). Migration triggers on config load via `load_or_generate_agent_configs()`.

### Data Flow

```
[AgentConfig with model_id] → [find ApiSource by api_source_id] → [find ModelDefinition by model_id] → [ModelConfig]
                                                                                                        ↓ fail
                                                                                          [fallback: first model + warn]
```

### Key Architecture Decisions

| Decision | Choice | Rationale |
|----------|--------|-----------|
| Model reference | `model_id: String` on AgentConfig | Direct, no ambiguity, no silent downgrade |
| Tier role | Display tag on ModelDefinition | User sees grouping; resolution ignores it |
| Migration strategy | Auto-fill on load | Zero user action; backward compatible |
| Fallback | First model in source + log warning | Always produces a valid config; visible in logs |

### Trade-offs

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| **Direct model_id (chosen)** | No silent downgrades, simple resolution, explicit | User must select model per agent |
| Tier downgrade walk | Automatic fallback | Silent quality degradation, unpredictable |
| LLM-selected model | Adaptive | Extra token cost, non-deterministic |

## ApiSources-A3 Model-First Agent Configuration Architecture
**Status:** approved
**Tags:** stack:both, module:api-sources
**Depends on:** ApiSources-G1, ApiSources-G3

### Overview

Replace tier-based model selection (`model_tier: ModelTier`) with direct model reference (`model_id: String`) in AgentConfig. Tier becomes a display-only tag on ModelDefinition. This eliminates the tier downgrade walk in `resolve_model()` and prevents misconfiguration when an ApiSource lacks models for certain tiers.

### Problem

The current `resolve_model()` walks through tiers (Min → Lite → Mid → Pro → Max) looking for any model that exists in the ApiSource. If an ApiSource only has Mid and Pro models, an agent configured for Lite silently gets Mid — which may be more expensive than intended. Users have no visibility into which actual model their agent uses.

### Solution

AgentConfig stores a direct `model_id` referencing a specific ModelDefinition in an ApiSource. The `resolve_model()` function does a single lookup by ID. Migration logic converts existing tier-based configs to concrete model IDs on load.

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph "Config Resolution"
        AC[AgentConfig.model_id] --> RM[resolve_model]
        AS[ApiSource.models] --> RM
        RM --> MC[ModelConfig]
    end
    subgraph "Migration Path"
        LEGACY[Legacy: model_tier only] --> AMI[assign_model_ids]
        AMI -->|tier → first matching model| AC
        NEW[New: model_id set] --> AC
    end
    subgraph "Fallback Chain"
        RM -->|model_id found| MC
        RM -->|model_id missing| LOG[log::warn + first model]
        RM -->|source missing| LOG2[log::warn + first source]
    end
```

### Trigger Condition

`resolve_model()` is called every time an agent is spawned (relay step or chat turn). Migration runs once on config load via `load_or_generate_agent_configs()`.

### Data Flow

```
[AgentConfig.model_id] + [ApiSource.models]
    → resolve_model() → find ModelDefinition by model_id
    → ModelConfig { provider, model, temperature, max_tokens, reasoning_budget }
```

### Design Highlight

Direct model reference is simpler, more predictable, and gives users exact control. The tier downgrade walk was a hidden behavior that surprised users when their "Lite" agent got upgraded to "Mid" without notice.

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| **Direct model_id reference** (chosen) | Explicit, predictable, no silent upgrades | User must pick a model; no auto-selection |
| Tier downgrade walk (current) | Works without user choice | Silent upgrades, unpredictable cost |
| LLM picks model at runtime | Adaptive | Non-deterministic cost, extra tokens |
